# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: verifiable-credentials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] A **decentralized identifier (DID)** is a type of globally unique identifier that enables an entity to be identified in a manner that is verifiable, persistent (as long as the DID controller desires), and does not require the use of a centralized registry.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] DIDs enable a new model of decentralized digital identity that is often referred to as a self-sovereign identity (SSI).
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The DIDs are an important component of decentralized web applications.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] A decentralized identifier resolves (points) to a **DID document**, a set of data describing the DID subject, including mechanisms, such as cryptographic public keys, that the DID subject or a DID delegate can use to authenticate itself and prove its association with the DID.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Just as there are many different types of URIs, all of which conform to the URI standard, there are many different types of **DID methods**, all of which must conform to the DID standard.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group maintains a registry of DID methods.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] A DID identifies any subject (e.g., a person, organization, thing, data model, abstract entity, etc.) that the controller of the DID decides that it identifies.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are designed to enable the controller of a DID to prove control over it and to be implemented independently of any centralized registry, identity provider, or certificate authority.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are URIs that associate a DID subject with a DID document.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Each DID document can express cryptographic material, verification methods, and service endpoints to enable trusted interactions associated with the DID subject.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might contain additional semantics about the subject that it identifies.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might also contain the DID subject itself (e.g. a data model).
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] National efforts include the European Digital Identity (EUDI) Wallet as a part of eIDAS 2.0 in the European Union, and China Real-Name Decentralized Identifier System (China RealDID) under China's Ministry of Public Security.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The AT Protocol and applications powered by the protocol such as Bluesky use DIDs for their identity system in order to give users full control over their identity, including where their data is stored.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The protocol uses its own DID method, did:plc, as well as a general domain-based method with did:web.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Persona is an identity verification company founded in 2018.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Its product consists of uploading a government-issued ID and potentially taking a selfie to confirm the user's identity and give them a DID identity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The service is used by the LinkedIn professional networking site, the Discord and Reddit social media networks, the Roblox video game platform, and the OpenAI artificial intelligence company.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is a privacy-focused digital identity solution developed by Polygon, a blockchain scaling platform.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] It leverages zero-knowledge proofs (ZKPs) to allow users to verify specific aspects of their identity—such as age or residency—without revealing underlying personal data.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] This enables secure and private interactions with services that require identity verification, such as financial platforms, voting systems, or DAO governance, while preserving user anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is already being explored by governments and organizations seeking compliant and privacy-preserving identity systems in Web3 environments.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group developed a specification for decentralized identifiers to standardize the core architecture, data model, and representation of DIDs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The W3C approved the DID 1.0 specification as a W3C Recommendation on July 19, 2022.
[src:verifiable-credentials/decentralized-identifier] The Decentralized Identity Foundation (DIF) published a Dynamic Traveler Profile Generation Specification in June 2023, for use cases in the travel industry.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Because of the still evolving, and sometimes conflicting, terminologies used in the fields of computer science, computer security, and cryptography, the term "digital credential" is used quite confusingly in these fields.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Sometimes passwords or other means of authentication are referred to as credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In operating system design, credentials are the properties of a process (such as its effective UID) that is used for determining its access rights.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] On other occasions, certificates and associated key material such as those stored in PKCS#12 and PKCS#15 are referred to as credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Digital badges are a form of digital credential that indicate an accomplishment, skill, quality or interest.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Digital badges can be earned in a variety of learning environments.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Money, in general, is not regarded as a form of qualification that is inherently linked to a specific individual, as the value of token money is perceived to reside independently.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] However, the emergence of digital assets, such as digital cash, has introduced a new set of challenges due to their susceptibility to replication.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Consequently, digital cash protocols have been developed with additional measures to mitigate the issue of double spending, wherein a coin is used for multiple transactions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Credentials, on the other hand, serve as tangible evidence of an individual's qualifications or attributes, acting as a validation of their capabilities.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] One notable example is the concept of E-Coins, which are exclusively assigned to individuals and are not transferable to others.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] These E-Coins can only be utilised in transactions with authorised merchants.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Anonymity is maintained for individuals as long as they ensure that a coin is spent only once.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] However, if an individual attempts to spend the same coin multiple times, their identity can be established, enabling the bank or relevant authority to take appropriate actions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The shared characteristic of being tied to an individual forms the basis for the numerous similarities between digital cash and digital credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] This commonality explains why these two concepts often exhibit overlapping features.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In fact, it is worth noting that a significant majority of implementations of anonymous digital credentials also incorporate elements of digital cash systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The concept of anonymous digital credentials centres around the provision of cryptographic tokens to users, enabling them to demonstrate specific statements about themselves and their associations with public and private organizations while maintaining anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] This approach is viewed as a privacy-conscious alternative to the storage and utilization of extensive centralized user records, which can be linked together.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Anonymous digital credentials are thus related to privacy and anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Analogous to the physical world, personalised or non-anonymous credentials include documents like passports, driving licenses, credit cards, health insurance cards, and club membership cards.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] These credentials bear the owner's name and possess certain validating features, such as signatures, PINs, or photographs, to prevent unauthorised usage.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In contrast, anonymous credentials in the physical realm can be exemplified by forms of currency, bus and train tickets, and game-arcade tokens.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] These items lack personally identifiable information, allowing for their transfer between users without the issuers or relying parties being aware of such transactions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Organizations responsible for issuing credentials verify the authenticity of the information contained within them, which can be provided to verifying entities upon request.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] To explore the specific privacy-related characteristics of credentials, it is instructive to examine two types of credentials: physical money and credit cards.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Both facilitate payment transactions effectively, although the extent and quality of information disclosed differ significantly.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Money is safeguarded against counterfeiting through its physical properties.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Furthermore, it reveals minimal information, with coins featuring an inherent value and year of minting, while banknotes incorporate a unique serial number to comply with traceability requirements for law enforcement purposes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In contrast, the usage of credit cards, despite sharing a fundamental purpose with money, allows for the generation of detailed records pertaining to the cardholder.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Consequently, credit cards are not considered protective of privacy.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The primary advantage of money, in terms of privacy, is that its users can preserve their anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] However, real-world cash also possesses additional security and usability features that contribute to its widespread acceptance.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Credentials utilised within a national identification system are particularly relevant to privacy considerations.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Such identification documents, including passports, driver's licenses, or other types of cards, typically contain essential personal information.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In certain scenarios, it may be advantageous to selectively disclose only specific portions of the information contained within the identification document.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] For example, it might be desirable to reveal only the minimum age of an individual or the fact that they are qualified to drive a car.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The original system of anonymous credentials, initially proposed by David Chaum is sometimes referred to as a pseudonym system.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] This nomenclature arises from the nature of the credentials within this system, which are acquired and presented to organizations under distinct pseudonyms that cannot be linked together.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The introduction of pseudonyms is a useful extension to anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] *Pseudonyms* represent a valuable expansion of anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] They afford users the ability to adopt different names when interacting with each organization.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] While pseudonyms enable organizations to establish associations with user accounts, they are unable to ascertain the true identities of their customers.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Nonetheless, through the utilisation of an anonymous credential, specific assertions concerning a user's relationship with one organization, under a pseudonym, can be verified by another organization that only recognizes the user under a different pseudonym.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Anonymous credential systems have a close connection to the concept of untraceable or anonymous payments.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] David Chaum made significant contributions to this field by introducing blind signature protocols as a novel cryptographic primitive.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In such protocols, the signer remains oblivious to the message being signed, while the recipient obtains a signature without any knowledge of the signed message.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Blind signatures serve as a crucial building block for various privacy-sensitive applications, including anonymous payments, voting systems, and credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The original notion of an anonymous credential system was derived from the concept of blind signatures but relied on a trusted party for the transfer of credentials, involving the translation from one pseudonym to another.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Chaum's blind signature scheme, based on RSA signatures and the discrete logarithm problem, enabled the construction of anonymous credential systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Stefan Brands further advanced digital credentials by introducing secret-key certificate-based credentials, enhancing Chaum's basic blind-signature system in both the discrete logarithm and strong RSA assumption settings.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Brands credentials offer efficient algorithms and unconditional commercial security in terms of privacy, along with additional features like a proof of non-membership blacklist.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Another form of credentials that adds a new feature to anonymous credentials is multi-show unlinkability, which is realized through group signature related credentials of Camenisch et al.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The introduction of Group signatures possibilities for multi-show unlinkable showing protocols.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] While blind signatures are highly relevant for electronic cash and single-show credentials, the cryptographic primitive known as group signature introduced new avenues for constructing privacy-enhancing protocols.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Group signatures share similarities with Chaum's concept of credential systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] In a group signature scheme, members of a group can sign a message using their respective secret keys.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The resulting signature can be verified by anyone possessing the common public key, without revealing any information about the signer other than their group membership.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Typically, a group manager entity exists, capable of disclosing the actual identity of the signer and managing the addition or removal of users from the group, often through the issuance or revocation of group membership certificates.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] The anonymity, unlinkability, and anonymity revocation features provided by group signatures make them suitable for various privacy-sensitive applications, such as voting, bidding, anonymous payments, and anonymous credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Efficient constructions for group signatures were presented by Ateniese, Camenisch, Joye, and Tsudik while the most efficient multi-show unlinkable anonymous credential systems]—with the latter being a streamlined version of idemix[]—are based on similar principles.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] This is particularly true for credential systems that provide efficient means for implementing anonymous multi-show credentials with credential revocation.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Both schemes are based on techniques for doing proofs of knowledge.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Proofs of knowledge based on the discrete logarithm problem for groups of known order and the special RSA problem for groups of hidden order form the foundation for most modern group signature and anonymous credential systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Moreover, the direct anonymous attestation, a protocol for authenticating trusted platform modules, is also based on the same techniques.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Direct anonymous attestation can be considered the first commercial application of multi-show anonymous digital credentials, although in this case, the credentials are associated with chips and computer platforms rather than individuals.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] From an application perspective, the main advantage of Camenisch et al.'s multi-show unlinkable credentials over the more efficient Brands credentials is the property of multi-show unlinkability.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] However, this property is primarily relevant in offline settings.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Brands credentials offer a mechanism that provides analogous functionality without sacrificing performance: an efficient batch issuing protocol capable of simultaneously issuing multiple unlinkable credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] This mechanism can be combined with a privacy-preserving certificate refresh process, which generates a fresh unlinkable credential with the same attributes as a previously spent credential.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] Online credentials for learning are digital credentials that are offered in place of traditional paper credentials for a skill or educational achievement.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-credential] It is useful to distinguish between three forms of online credentials: Test-based credentials, online badges, and online certificates.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:verifiable-credentials/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials can be issued by anyone, about anything, and can be presented to and verified by everyone.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The entity that generates the credential is called the *Issuer*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The credential is then given to the *Holder* who stores it for later use.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The Holder can then prove something about themselves by presenting their credentials to a *Verifier*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a verifiable credential operates in a triangle of trust, mediating between issuer and verifier.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Any role in the triangle can be played by a person, an institution, or a machine.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Note that because verifiable credentials can be created by anyone, the verifier decides if they trust the issuer.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The VC model places the holder of a credential at the center of the identity ecosystem, giving individuals control of their identity attributes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The W3C VC model parallels physical credentials: the user holds cards and can present them to anyone at any time without informing or requiring the permission of the card issuer.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Such a model is decentralized and gives much more autonomy and privacy to the participants.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] This contrasts with the federated identity management (FIM) model, as adopted by SAML and OpenID Connect, which place the identity provider (IdP) in the central role as the dispenser of identity attributes and the determiner of which Service Providers (SPs) it will give them to.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] In the federated model, the IdP knows every SP that the user visits.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The data model for verifiable credentials is a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Recommendation, "Verifiable Credentials Data Model 1.0 - Expressing verifiable information on the Web", published 19 November 2019.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The VC context, defined using the `@context` JSON property, is a JSON-LD construct that allows user friendly terms to be used for JSON properties.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] According to the VC data model, the value of many properties must be a URI.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Whilst these are globally unambiguous, (important for a global data model), they are not user-friendly.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Consequently, the `@context` property allows short-form, user-friendly aliases to be defined for each URI.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] This makes it much easier, and more user-friendly, to specify VCs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Any new property can be added to VCs, as determined by the issuer.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Standard properties have been defined specifically as extension points.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a VC does not always have to be the subject of the credential.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] It is expected that most users will hold their own VCs, i.e., the holder and the subject will be the same entity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] For example, when the VC subject is an infant, and the VC is a birth certificate, the holder may be one or both parents.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] No proof mechanism is standardized but the data model is flexible enough to support various existing cryptographic mechanisms, such as digital signatures.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Proof mechanisms that are in use include: JSON Web Tokens with JSON Web Signatures, JSON-LD proofs, and zero-knowledge proofs using schemes such as IBM's anonymous credentials.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Various protocols are specified for carrying VCs from the issuer/IdP to the holder, and the holder to the verifier.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] None of these protocols has become standardized.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Many people who are experimenting with VCs use HTTPS to carry VCs between the various parties.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] The security of verifiable credentials in the context of COVID-19 vaccination and test certificates has been questioned.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials have also been subject to usability concerns.
[src:verifiable-credentials/verifiable-credentials] Some have likened anyone being able to issue a verifiable credential being like a shop clerk deciding if they should accept an out-of-state license as proof of age when purchasing alcohol.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The intuition behind the nontriviality of zero-knowledge proofs is that it is trivial to prove possession of the relevant information simply by revealing it; the hard part is to prove this possession without revealing this information (or any aspect of it whatsoever).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs can be interactive, meaning that the prover and verifier exchange messages according to some protocol, or noninteractive, meaning that the verifier is convinced by a single prover message and no other communication is needed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In the standard model, interaction is required, except for trivial proofs of BPP problems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In the common random string and random oracle models, non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs exist.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The Fiat–Shamir heuristic can be used to transform certain interactive zero-knowledge proofs into noninteractive ones.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] One example of a math-free zero-knowledge proof is if Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she has drawn a red card from a standard deck of 52 playing cards, without revealing which specific red card she holds.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor observes Peggy draw a card at random from the shuffled deck, but she keeps the card face-down so he cannot see it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] To prove her card is red without revealing its identity, Peggy takes the remaining 51 cards from the deck and systematically shows Victor all 26 black cards (the 13 spades and 13 clubs) one by one, placing them face-up on the table.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Since a standard deck contains exactly 26 red cards and 26 black cards, and Peggy has demonstrated that all the black cards remain in the deck, Victor can conclude with certainty that Peggy's hidden card must be red.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This proof is zero-knowledge because Victor learns only that Peggy's card is red, but gains no information about whether it is a heart or diamond, or which specific red card she holds.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The proof would be equally convincing whether Peggy held the Ace of Hearts or the Two of Diamonds.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Furthermore, even if the interaction were recorded, the recording would not reveal Peggy's specific card to future observers, maintaining the zero-knowledge property.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy were lying and actually held a black card, she would be unable to produce all 26 black cards from the remaining deck, making deception impossible.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This demonstrates the soundness of the proof system.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This type of physical zero-knowledge proof using standard playing cards belongs to a broader class of card-based cryptographic protocols that allow participants to perform secure computations using everyday objects.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Another well-known example of a zero-knowledge proof is the "Where's Waldo" example.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In this example, the prover has a page from a *Where's Waldo?* children's book, which shows many hundreds of cartoon people, where only one of them is the visually distinctive character of Waldo.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover wants to prove to the verifier that they know where Waldo is on the page, without revealing his location to the verifier.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover starts by taking a large black board with a small hole in it, the size of Waldo.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The board is twice the size of the book in both directions, so the verifier cannot see where on the page the prover is placing it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover then places the board over the page so that Waldo is in the hole.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The verifier can now look through the hole and see Waldo, but cannot see any other part of the page.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, the prover has proven to the verifier that they know where Waldo is, without revealing any other information about his location.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This example is not a perfect zero-knowledge proof, because the prover does reveal some information about Waldo's location, such as his body position.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, it is a decent illustration of the basic concept of a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B, while Victor waits outside.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy reliably appears at the exit Victor names.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] There is a well-known story presenting the fundamental ideas of zero-knowledge proofs, first published in 1990 by Jean-Jacques Quisquater and others in their paper "How to Explain Zero-Knowledge Protocols to Your Children".
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The two parties in the zero-knowledge proof story are Peggy as the prover of the statement, and Victor, the verifier of the statement.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In this story, Peggy has uncovered the secret word used to open a magic door in a cave.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The cave is shaped like a ring, with the entrance on one side and the magic door blocking the opposite side.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor wants to know whether Peggy knows the secret word; but Peggy, being a very private person, does not want to reveal her knowledge (the secret word) to Victor or to reveal the fact of her knowledge to the world in general.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] They label the paths from the entrance A and B.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] First, Victor waits outside the cave as Peggy goes in.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B; Victor is not allowed to see which path she takes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, Victor enters the cave and shouts the name of the path he wants her to use to return, either A or B, chosen at random.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Providing she really does know the magic word, this is easy: she opens the door, if necessary, and returns along the desired path.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, suppose she did not know the word.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, she would only be able to return by the named path if Victor were to give the name of the same path by which she had entered.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Since Victor would choose A or B at random, she would have a 50% chance of guessing correctly.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If they were to repeat this trick many times, say 20 times in a row, her chance of successfully anticipating all of Victor's requests would be reduced to 1 in 220, or 9.54 × 10−7.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, if Peggy repeatedly appears at the exit Victor names, then he can conclude that it is extremely probable that Peggy does, in fact, know the secret word.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] With respect to third-party observers: even if Victor is wearing a hidden camera that records the whole transaction, the only thing the camera will record is in one case Victor shouting "A!" and Peggy appearing at A or in the other case Victor shouting "B!" and Peggy appearing at B.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A recording of this type would be trivial for any two people to fake (requiring only that Peggy and Victor agree beforehand on the sequence of As and Bs that Victor will shout).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Such a recording will certainly never be convincing to anyone but the original participants.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In fact, even a person who was present as an observer at the original experiment should be unconvinced, since Victor and Peggy could have orchestrated the whole "experiment" from start to finish.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Further, if Victor chooses his As and Bs by flipping a coin on-camera, this protocol loses its zero-knowledge property; the on-camera coin flip would probably be convincing to any person watching the recording later.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, although this does not reveal the secret word to Victor, it does make it possible for Victor to convince the world in general that Peggy has that knowledge—counter to Peggy's stated wishes.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, digital cryptography generally "flips coins" by relying on a pseudo-random number generator, which is akin to a coin with a fixed pattern of heads and tails known only to the coin's owner.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Victor's coin behaved this way, then again it would be possible for Victor and Peggy to have faked the experiment, so using a pseudo-random number generator would not reveal Peggy's knowledge to the world in the same way that using a flipped coin would.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy could prove to Victor that she knows the magic word, without revealing it to him, in a single trial.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If both Victor and Peggy go together to the mouth of the cave, Victor can watch Peggy go in through A and come out through B.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This would prove with certainty that Peggy knows the magic word, without revealing the magic word to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, such a proof could be observed by a third party, or recorded by Victor and such a proof would be convincing to anybody.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, Peggy could not refute such proof by claiming she colluded with Victor, and she is therefore no longer in control of who is aware of her knowledge.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Imagine Victor is red-green color-blind (while Peggy is not) and Peggy has two balls: one red and one green, but otherwise identical.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] To Victor, the balls seem completely identical.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor is skeptical that the balls are actually distinguishable.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to *prove to Victor that the balls are in fact differently colored*, but nothing else.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In particular, Peggy does not want to reveal which ball is the red one and which is the green.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Here is the proof system: Peggy gives the two balls to Victor and he puts them behind his back.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Next, he takes one of the balls and brings it out from behind his back and displays it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] He then places it behind his back again and then chooses to reveal just one of the two balls, picking one of the two at random with equal probability.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] He will ask Peggy, "Did I switch the ball?" This whole procedure is then repeated as often as necessary.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] By looking at the balls' colors, Peggy can, of course, say with certainty whether or not he switched them.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the balls were the same color and hence indistinguishable, Peggy's ability to determine whether a switch occurred would be no better than random guessing.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Since the probability that Peggy would have randomly succeeded at identifying each switch/non-switch is 50%, the probability of having randomly succeeded at *all* switch/non-switches approaches zero.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Over multiple trials, the success rate would statistically converge to 50%, and Peggy could not achieve a performance significantly better than chance.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy and Victor repeat this "proof" multiple times (e.g.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] 20 times), Victor should become convinced that the balls are indeed differently colored.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The above proof is *zero-knowledge* because Victor never learns which ball is green and which is red; indeed, he gains no knowledge about how to distinguish the balls.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] **Soundness**: if the statement is false, then no cheating prover can convince an honest verifier that it is true, except with some small probability.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] **Zero-knowledge**: if the statement is true, then no verifier learns anything other than the fact that the statement is true.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, just knowing the statement (not the secret) is sufficient to imagine a scenario showing that the prover knows the secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This is formalized by showing that every verifier has some *simulator* that, given only the statement to be proved (and no access to the prover), can produce a transcript that "looks like" an interaction between an honest prover and the verifier in question.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The first two of these are properties of more general interactive proof systems.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The third is what makes the proof zero-knowledge.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs are not proofs in the mathematical sense of the term because there is some small probability, the *soundness error*, that a cheating prover will be able to convince the verifier of a false statement.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, zero-knowledge proofs are probabilistic "proofs" rather than deterministic proofs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, there are techniques to decrease the soundness error to negligibly small values (for example, guessing correctly on a hundred or thousand binary decisions has a 1/2100 or 1/21000 soundness error, respectively.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] As the number of bits increases, the soundness error decreases toward zero).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A formal definition of zero-knowledge must use some computational model, the most common one being that of a Turing machine.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover P is modeled as having unlimited computation power (in practice, P usually is a probabilistic Turing machine).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Intuitively, the definition states that an interactive proof system (*P*,*V*) is zero-knowledge if for any verifier ${\hat {V}}$ there exists an efficient simulator S (depending on ${\hat {V}}$ ) that can reproduce the conversation between P and ${\hat {V}}$ on any given input.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The auxiliary string z in the definition plays the role of "prior knowledge" (including the random coins of ${\hat {V}}$ ).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition implies that ${\hat {V}}$ cannot use any prior knowledge string z to mine information out of its conversation with P, because if S is also given this prior knowledge then it can reproduce the conversation between ${\hat {V}}$ and P just as before.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition given is that of perfect zero-knowledge.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Computational zero-knowledge is obtained by requiring that the views of the verifier ${\hat {V}}$ and the simulator are only computationally indistinguishable, given the auxiliary string.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] These ideas can be applied to a more realistic cryptography application.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she knows the discrete logarithm of a given value in a given group.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, given a value y, a large prime p, and a generator g , she wants to prove that she knows a value x such that *g**x* ≡ *y* (mod *p*), without revealing x.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The protocol proceeds as follows: in each round, Peggy generates a random number r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p* and discloses this to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] After receiving C, Victor randomly issues one of the following two requests: he either requests that Peggy discloses the value of r, or the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor can verify either answer; if he requested r, he can then compute *g**r* mod *p* and verify that it matches C.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If he requested (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then he can verify that C is consistent with this, by computing *g*(*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) mod *p* and verifying that it matches (*C* · *y*) mod *p*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy indeed knows the value of x, then she can respond to either one of Victor's possible challenges.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if she knows that Victor will request (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then she picks a random value *r*′, computes *C*′ ≡ *g**r*′ · (*g**x*)−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ to Victor as the value of C that he is expecting.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] When Victor challenges her to reveal (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), she reveals *r*′, for which Victor will verify consistency, since he will in turn compute *g**r*′ mod *p*, which matches *C*′ · *y*, since Peggy multiplied by the modular multiplicative inverse of y.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, if in either one of the above scenarios Victor issues a challenge other than the one she was expecting and for which she manufactured the result, then she will be unable to respond to the challenge under the assumption of infeasibility of solving the discrete log for this group.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If she picked r and disclosed *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, then she will be unable to produce a valid (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) that would pass Victor's verification, given that she does not know x.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, a cheating prover has a 0.5 probability of successfully cheating in one round.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] By executing a large-enough number of rounds, the probability of a cheating prover succeeding can be made arbitrarily low.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] To show that the above interactive proof gives zero knowledge other than the fact that Peggy knows x, one can use similar arguments as used in the above proof of completeness and soundness.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Specifically, a simulator, say Simon, who does not know x, can simulate the exchange between Peggy and Victor by the following procedure.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Firstly, Simon randomly flips a fair coin.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If the result is "heads", then he picks a random value r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, and discloses C as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon also outputs a message "request the value of r" as if it is sent from Victor to Peggy, and immediately outputs the value of r as if it is sent from Peggy to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the coin flipping result is "tails", then Simon picks a random number *r*′, computes *C*′ = *g**r*′ · *y*−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon outputs "request the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1)" as if it is a message from Victor to Peggy.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, Simon outputs the value of *r*′ as if it is the response from Peggy back to Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] By the previous arguments when proving the completeness and soundness, the interactive communication simulated by Simon is indistinguishable from the true correspondence between Peggy and Victor.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero-knowledge property is thus guaranteed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The following scheme is due to Manuel Blum.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In this scenario, Peggy knows a Hamiltonian cycle for a large graph G.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor knows G but not the cycle (e.g., Peggy has generated G and revealed it to him.) Finding a Hamiltonian cycle given a large graph is believed to be computationally infeasible, since its corresponding decision version is known to be NP-complete.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy will prove that she knows the cycle without simply revealing it (perhaps Victor is interested in buying it but wants verification first, or maybe Peggy is the only one who knows this information and is proving her identity to Victor).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] It is important that the commitment to the graph be such that Victor can verify, in the second case, that the cycle is really made of edges from H.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This can be done by, for example, committing to every edge (or lack thereof) separately.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does know a Hamiltonian cycle in G, then she can easily satisfy Victor's demand for either the graph isomorphism producing H from G (which she had committed to in the first step) or a Hamiltonian cycle in H (which she can construct by applying the isomorphism to the cycle in G).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy's answers do not reveal the original Hamiltonian cycle in G.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In each round, Victor will learn only H's isomorphism to G or a Hamiltonian cycle in H.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] He would need both answers for a single H to discover the cycle in G, so the information remains unknown as long as Peggy can generate a distinct H every round.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know of a Hamiltonian cycle in G, but somehow knew in advance what Victor would ask to see each round, then she could cheat.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, if Peggy knew ahead of time that Victor would ask to see the Hamiltonian cycle in H, then she could generate a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Similarly, if Peggy knew in advance that Victor would ask to see the isomorphism then she could simply generate an isomorphic graph H (in which she also does not know a Hamiltonian cycle).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor could simulate the protocol by himself (without Peggy) because he knows what he will ask to see.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, Victor gains no information about the Hamiltonian cycle in G from the information revealed in each round.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know the information, then she can guess which question Victor will ask and generate either a graph isomorphic to G or a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph, but since she does not know a Hamiltonian cycle for G, she cannot do both.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] With this guesswork, her chance of fooling Victor is 2−*n*, where n is the number of rounds.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] For all realistic purposes, it is infeasibly difficult to defeat a zero-knowledge proof with a reasonable number of rounds in this way.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proof schemes can be constructed from various cryptographic primitives, such as hash-based cryptography, pairing-based cryptography, multi-party computation, or lattice-based cryptography.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Generally, zero-knowledge proofs are used within protocols to enforce honest behavior while maintaining privacy.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Roughly, the idea is to force a user to prove, using a zero-knowledge proof, that their behavior is correct according to the protocol.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Research in zero-knowledge proofs has been motivated by authentication systems where one party wants to prove its identity to a second party via some secret information (such as a password) but does not want the second party to learn anything about this secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This is called a "zero-knowledge proof of knowledge".
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] However, a password is typically too small or insufficiently random to be used in many schemes for zero-knowledge proofs of knowledge.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A zero-knowledge password proof is a special kind of zero-knowledge proof of knowledge that addresses the limited size of passwords.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In April 2015, the one-out-of-many proofs protocol (a Sigma protocol) was introduced.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In August 2021, Cloudflare, an American web infrastructure and security company, decided to use the one-out-of-many proofs mechanism for private web verification using vendor hardware.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] In 2016, the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory and Princeton University demonstrated a technique that may have applicability to future nuclear disarmament talks.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] It would allow inspectors to confirm whether or not an object is indeed a nuclear weapon without recording, sharing, or revealing the internal workings, which might be secret.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were applied in the Zerocoin and Zerocash protocols, which culminated in the birth of Zcoin (later rebranded as Firo in 2020) and Zcash cryptocurrencies in 2016.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zerocoin has a built-in mixing model that does not trust any peers or centralized mixing providers to ensure anonymity.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Users can transact in a base currency and can cycle the currency into and out of Zerocoins.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The Zerocash protocol uses a similar model (a variant known as a non-interactive zero-knowledge proof) except that it can obscure the transaction amount, while Zerocoin cannot.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Bulletproofs are an improvement from non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs where a trusted setup is not needed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Because of asymmetric signatures in documents such as passports and emails, zero knowledge proofs can be made of people's identities in order to privately verify information about themselves.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] For instance, you can prove that you are over 18 to a website, without revealing other details like your exact name or country of origin, by proving in zero knowledge that you own a passport signed by a valid government key for an age value over 18.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] By similarly making zero-knowledge proofs of the DKIM signatures of their emails, people can prove that they ordered or transferred a domain or concert ticket, own some handle on a social media service, or ordered something on an e-commerce service.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero knowledge property allows people to keep their own identity and email address private while doing so.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] These can be used to enable private and fair elections, low-fee secondary marketplaces, and whistleblowing services.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A related line of work applies zero-knowledge proofs to database analytics via so-called zero-knowledge "coprocessors": off-chain systems that execute queries and return both the result and a proof that the computation was performed correctly on untampered data.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Academic prototypes have shown how to produce ZK proofs for ad-hoc SQL queries while hiding inputs and guaranteeing correctness of the result (e.g., ZKSQL).
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were first conceived in 1985 by Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Charles Rackoff in their paper "The Knowledge Complexity of Interactive Proof-Systems".
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This paper introduced the IP hierarchy of interactive proof systems (*see interactive proof system*) and conceived the concept of *knowledge complexity*, a measurement of the amount of knowledge about the proof transferred from the prover to the verifier.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] They also gave the first zero-knowledge proof for a concrete problem, that of deciding quadratic nonresidues mod *m*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Together with a paper by László Babai and Shlomo Moran, this landmark paper invented interactive proof systems, for which all five authors won the first Gödel Prize in 1993.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The quadratic nonresidue problem has both an NP and a co-NP algorithm, and so lies in the intersection of NP and co-NP.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This was also true of several other problems for which zero-knowledge proofs were subsequently discovered, such as an unpublished proof system by Oded Goldreich verifying that a two-prime modulus is not a Blum integer.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali, and Avi Wigderson took this one step further, showing that, assuming the existence of unbreakable encryption, one can create a zero-knowledge proof system for the NP-complete graph coloring problem with three colors.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Since every problem in NP can be efficiently reduced to this problem, this means that, under this assumption, all problems in NP have zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The reason for the assumption is that, as in the above example, their protocols require encryption.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A commonly cited sufficient condition for the existence of unbreakable encryption is the existence of one-way functions, but it is conceivable that some physical means might also achieve it.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] On top of this, they also showed that the graph nonisomorphism problem, the complement of the graph isomorphism problem, has a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] This problem is in co-NP, but is not currently known to be in either NP or any practical class.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Not liking to make unnecessary assumptions, many theorists sought a way to eliminate the necessity of one way functions.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] One way this was done was with *multi-prover interactive proof systems* (see interactive proof system), which have multiple independent provers instead of only one, allowing the verifier to "cross-examine" the provers in isolation to avoid being misled.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] It can be shown that, without any intractability assumptions, all languages in NP have zero-knowledge proofs in such a system.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] It turns out that, in an Internet-like setting, where multiple protocols may be executed concurrently, building zero-knowledge proofs is more challenging.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The line of research investigating concurrent zero-knowledge proofs was initiated by the work of Dwork, Naor, and Sahai.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] One particular development along these lines has been the development of witness-indistinguishable proof protocols.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] The property of witness-indistinguishability is related to that of zero-knowledge, yet witness-indistinguishable protocols do not suffer from the same problems of concurrent execution.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Another variant of zero-knowledge proofs are non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Blum, Feldman, and Micali showed that a common random string shared between the prover and the verifier is enough to achieve computational zero-knowledge without requiring interaction.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A list of zero-knowledge proof protocols and libraries is provided below along with comparisons based on *transparency*, *universality*, *plausible post-quantum security*, and *programming paradigm*.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A transparent protocol is one that does not require any trusted setup and uses public randomness.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A universal protocol is one that does not require a separate trusted setup for each circuit.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, a plausibly post-quantum protocol is one that is not susceptible to known attacks involving quantum algorithms.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] While zero-knowledge proofs offer a secure way to verify information, the arithmetic circuits that implement them must be carefully designed.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] If these circuits lack sufficient constraints, they may introduce subtle yet critical security vulnerabilities.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] One of the most common classes of vulnerabilities in these systems is under-constrained logic, where insufficient constraints allow a malicious prover to produce a proof for an incorrect statement that still passes verification.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A 2024 systematization of known attacks found that approximately 96% of documented circuit-layer bugs in SNARK-based systems were due to under-constrained circuits.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] These vulnerabilities often arise during the translation of high-level logic into low-level constraint systems, particularly when using domain-specific languages such as Circom or Gnark.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Recent research has demonstrated that formally proving determinism – ensuring that a circuit's outputs are uniquely determined by its inputs – can eliminate entire classes of these vulnerabilities.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge virtual machines (zkVMs) are general-purpose virtual computers designed to execute code and generate zero-knowledge proofs that verify off-chain, without revealing private inputs, that the code ran correctly and produced the claimed result.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] A proof is a compact, structured binary file that can be efficiently checked by anyone using the zkVM's verifier tool without re-running the original computation.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] zkVMs have both development and security benefits.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Using a zkVM, developers can execute and verify complex computations off-chain, avoiding high on-chain "gas costs" (blockchain processing fees) and maintaining the privacy of code or data.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Several recently developed zkVMs, such as those developed by RISC Zero and Succinct Labs, support the RISC-V instruction set, which allows programmers to write code in mainstream programming languages like Rust instead of using a domain-specific circuit language such as Circom.
[src:verifiable-credentials/zero-knowledge-proof] Other zkVMs take different approaches, targeting WebAssembly (WASM) or implementing custom instruction sets optimized for zero-knowledge performance or integration with particular blockchain environments.
